{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9658cd2c-b7d1-48a3-84e8-9681de502b65","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request** — each request is a natural scope boundary. In MAUI, there's no equivalent boundary. The app uses a single long-lived scope, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`.\n\nYour DbContext is reused across navigations, accumulating tracked entities and stale data.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — new instance each time it's injected.\n2. **Create scopes manually** via `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n3. **Call `ChangeTracker.Clear()`** on navigation if you want to keep scoped registration but reset state.\n\n`AddTransient` is the simplest fix for most MAUI scenarios with EF Core.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1095a5af-01c5-4504-bfff-f329ca206164","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping behavior. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request — each request is a \"scope.\" But in MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request. The default DI container in MAUI creates a single scope for the entire application lifetime, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. This means the DbContext is reused across page navigations, causing stale/cached data to persist.","outputTokens":395,"requestId":"A842:2A55B4:6E1859:7F3A70:69FBE4CF"},"id":"8cf26958-0da5-45ad-b542-a00c6e8cfc37","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:03:21.962Z","parentId":"d6aa7fcd-3c49-4816-9d5e-43fd752116c5"}
